text=:Category: Varia%0a:Essential: {Category.Varia$:essential}%0a:Title: Adjectives as Adverbs in Conversational American English%0a:Author: Mihir_D%0a:Section: A%0a:Completed: 07.05.2021 - 23:00%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a----%0a%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210511-000349-280130#%0a* [-10.05.2021 - 17:03-] || TA_audrey marked as complete%0a#foxend 210511-000349-280130#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0aSummary: \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aSpeakers of American English tend to use adjective forms of adverbs far more often than British English speakers.%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aFor the purposes of casual conversation, many American English (AmE) speakers use the shorter adjectival forms of adverbs quite frequently. Online, I have seen British English (BrE) speakers point this out as "bad grammar", but I argue that it is just a dialectal difference which follows its own set of rules.%0a%0aHere are some examples (from https://separatedbyacommonlanguage.blogspot.com/2007/01/could-not-care-less-adverbs.html and https://learningenglish.voanews.com/a/adverbs-and-adjectives/3702382.html):%0a%0aHe did it real(ADJ) well. vs He did it really(ADV) well.%0aHe did it real(ADJ) good(ADJ). vs He did it really(ADV) well(ADV).%0aShe did that so cute(ADJ). vs She did that so cutely(ADV).%0aToday is going slow(ADJ). vs Today is going slowly(ADV).%0a%0aAll of these examples can be grammatical in conversational AmE (though some may be more than others), however an average BrE speaker would not say the ones on the left. AmE speakers are also starting to use some of these adjectives in less casual contexts (such as the last example or "it works great" in a work email). There is a trend these forms being accepted more and more in the US and the UK, so some BrE speakers blame Americans for this "degradation" of the language. However, some British dialects already have had the same pattern. Additionally, the pattern has some rules and syntax of its own. %0a%0aFor one thing, only adverbs that modify verbs or other adverbs tend to be replaced with adjectives. Another interesting point is where in a sentence the adjective-adverbs can be used compared to regular adverbs.%0a%0aExamples (from https://www.chronicle.com/blogs/linguafranca/the-americans-have-no-adverbs):%0a[1] You should eat it up "quickly"(ADV) before someone else gets it.%0a[2] You should "quickly"(ADV) eat it up before someone else gets it.%0a[3] You should eat it up "quick"(ADJ) before someone else gets it.%0a[4] *You should "quick"(ADJ) eat it up before someone else gets it.%0a%0a[1] and [2] show that the adverb form can be placed before or after the verb "eat". [3] and [4] show that the adjective form only works after the verb.%0a  %0aI think these adjectives are perfectly intelligible in place of adverbs in the cases they are used, so they are convenient short forms. I also understand if BrE speakers think this sentence reads "unnatural". *But you couldn't say it's "unequivocal" wrong. *Nor could you say this one "great" works.%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:GradedBy: TA_audrey:)
